    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies for the confusion. In the house-buying process, the third party, often referred to as the escrow agent, plays a crucial role in ensuring a smooth and secure transaction. The escrow agent is an impartial party, usually a bank or a title company, that holds the buyer's and seller's funds in a secure account until all the conditions of the sale are met. Here's how it works:\n\n1. The buyer and seller agree on the terms of the sale, including the price and closing date.\n2. The buyer provides a deposit to the escrow agent, which is typically a percentage of the purchase price.\n3. The seller provides the remaining funds to the escrow agent, usually through a check or electronic transfer.\n4. The escrow agent holds both the buyer's deposit and the seller's funds in a separate account.\n5. The escrow agent verifies that all the conditions of the sale have been met, including a satisfactory home inspection, the completion of necessary repairs, and the fulfillment of any other agreed-upon contingencies.\n6. Once all conditions are met, the escrow agent releases the funds to the seller, and the buyer receives the keys to the house.\n\nBy involving a third party, the escrow process helps to ensure that both the",
